Prologue.
"I implore you!" Queen Eirwen begged, "don't send her away! She's still a child!" The Ice King, accompanied by his royal advisor, looked down from his throne at his wife, who had given birth to a girl. At the thought, his expression darkened.
The girl resembled her mother very much. She had pale blue eyes and white hair with blue streaks. A girl meant weakness in the eyes of the Ice King. In the end, he had fathered only sons up to this point.
"You have two choices: either you kill the child or you send it into the wilderness. That is its punishment for your failure, Eirwen." He spat out her name as if it were poison. He always did.
Frostfell was not always a single kingdom. Earlier it consisted of two parts, the North and the South. In the North lay the non-magical kingdom, in the South a kingdom full of fantastic powers. But the North showed its greed and a never-ending war broke out between the two kingdoms, until the South finally offered a ceasefire.
The desperation in the south was so great that the royal family was willing to do anything to stop the bloodshed. They proposed sending their only princess to the north, where she would bear a son, the future king. In this case, the north would join with the south to form a kingdom. The north accepted the proposal and Princess Eirwen married Prince Akull.
"I implore you, my king, do with me as you wish, imprison me, banish me or kill me, but spare my child," Queen Eirwen pleaded, holding her child in her arms.
The Ice King looked down at his queen with full disgust. Maybe, but only maybe, he would have mercy on her. With the woman, whom he had been married to for 22 years, who had stood by him in his worst times and who had given him his sons.
"Alright. The child can stay at the palace," he said, which was noted by the queen with a sigh. "But," he added, "you will be executed."
The royal advisor and Queen Eirwen looked at each other in horror. Slowly she turned her gaze to the ground. "Yes, my king." She bowed.
The Ice King ordered the royal advisor to bring the queen's daughter into one of Eirwen's free rooms. Subsequently, he commanded the guards to take Eirwen to the gallows, where all citizens of the city could see.
While the guards escorted them to the gallows, a loud commotion arose among the citizens as they realized their beloved only queen was to be executed. Some people wept, others screamed and attacked the guards, while others wondered why this was happening, but everyone was in agreement.
"Let her go!"
"Why are they doing that to her?"
As Eirwen approached the wooden stake, the most feared person in the kingdom appeared. The Fire Judge. The woman who was still queen was to be burned. No one deserved such a death, not even criminals. It was the most horrific thing one could do to a human in Frostfell.
Eirwen was bound to the wooden stake, and the king declared in a speech how the queen had betrayed them all. The inhabitants of Frostfell refused to believe the king and would not accept his words. Then the firebrand ignited the wooden stake, and a single tear rolled down the face of the former queen.
"Don't give up, Kari. This was the end of Queen Eirwen's reign."
Funereal silence in the palace.
Only the sound of knocking was coming from the room located all the way to the left in the south wing of the palace, which was always freezing cold. The servants who passed by were always wondering what was in the room. They were afraid of it. In the palace, rumors were being spread among the maids. It was allegedly said that the deceased wife of the Ice King, Eirwen, was in this room and waiting to be let out.
Her assumption couldn't have been more wrong, thought Ivory and headed towards the southern wing, while the staff scurried about and whispered to each other. They had no idea what was hiding behind the door.
The rumors also concerned Ivory, as Ivory was the only one allowed to enter the room.
Knock, knock. "Lady Kari, are you in there?" Ivory whispered before the door, decorated with snowflakes and a crown, the symbol of the royal family.
Ivory wondered if – unlike the last attempt – access would actually be granted. I still have bruises from the last time. Ivory giggled at the thought. Kari had thrown a book against Ivory's shoulder, but apologized immediately when she realized who she had hit.
A single knock was audible from within, probably to say that she was there. Where else would she be?
"May I enter?", Ivory asked. Earlier, Ivory had gone in without asking.
From within, Ivory heard a knocking. That likely meant a "yes". The cold and the sound made Ivory shudder. It felt strange to hear a sound from a room supposedly empty, despite Ivory having entered it for several years already.
"I'm coming in," said Ivory and slowly opened the door. The sight that was offered to Ivory in the room was unusual for normal people, but not unexpected for Ivory. There was paper everywhere, books were scattered, the desk was broken and several ice sculptures were lying around. There were no windows and very little or no light. Also, it was colder than the rest of the palace (which said a lot). The room looked as if a snowstorm had swept through.
The girl lay rolled up in her bed, wrapped in her blanket, and read in one of her notebooks. A small lantern lit the room.
"What notebook is that?", Ivory asked and sat down beside Kari on the bed."
